</p><textarea readonly="" accesskey="," id="wpTextbox1" cols="80" rows="25" style="" lang="en" dir="ltr" name="wpTextbox1">== Kotor on Linux ==

Knights of the Old Republic is an old Windows games for playing in the old "Expanded Universe" of Star Wars. Good Old Games worked their fantastic updating and patching magic on it and now it's very easy to install on Linux, through Wine. It's nice to be able to play it without any no-CD hacks.

=== Configuration Tricks ===

edit the "swkotor.ini" file
&lt;pre>
[Graphics Options]
FullScreen=0&lt;/pre>

When set to 0, you run in windowed mode.

Toggle between Windowed and Full Screen mode
&lt;pre>[Graphics Options]
AllowWindowedMode=1&lt;/pre>

allows you to switch from fullscreen to window and vice versa by pressing ALT-Enter

To allow cheats:
&lt;pre>[Game Options]
EnableCheats=1 
&lt;/pre>
=== Mods ===

Definitely get recruitable Kay, the Bastila romance fix, and Solomons Revenge (which is pretty much a DLC package)

* [http://www.jumpstationz.com/RedHawke/mods.html Redhawke's Mods] - Includes making Carth, Misson, and Canderous into Jedi.

* Make Mission a Jedi. She makes a good Jedi Sentinel. Make sure to boost her wisdom as she levels.

* Make Carth a Jedi. Carth should be a Jedi Guardian.

=== Widescreen Fix ===
[http://www.wsgf.org/article/star-wars-knights-old-republic Widescreen For KOTOR 1]

Follow the directions but use the 800x600 base resolution.

== KOTOR 2: The Sith Lords on Linux ==

I'm really glad to have the GOG version.

For those who don't:

=== Clean Setup ===

I have the GOG package, but before that I picked up a box DVD set that has both games on two disks with all patches and updated quality files.

* Mount ISO of my install DVD using AcetoneISO.
* Use the crosstie to install in a fresh Windows XP bottle in Crossover.
* Change the graphics settings to emulate a virtual desktop (on cowspot: 1920 x 1200) + don't let it decorate the windows.
* If you don't already have it (I do), install higher quality movies and sound files.
* If you don't already have it (I do), install official 1.0b patch. Note: do NOT use 1.0c. That's an unofficial fan patch and is not compatible with the mod.

This is equivalent to starting with a Steam install or the GOG install.

If you do have the GOG version:

* Install using the GOG installer.
* Change the graphics settings to emulate a virtual desktop (on cowspot: 1920 x 1200) + don't let it decorate the windows.

=== The Restored Content Mod (and Planet M4-78) ===

The [http://deadlystream.com/forum/files/file/398-tslrcm-183/ Restored Content Mod] seeks to restore content included by Obsidian but left incomplete or dropped because Activision demanded the game be released early. Many object, audio, and text dialogue files were left intact, but disconnected from the existing quest lines. The Modding team found these files and, like a jigsaw puzzle, figured out how to re-assemble them. Kudos to everyone involved in the restoration efforts!

Planet [http://deadlystream.com/forum/files/file/399-m4-78ep-patched/ M4-78] was also meant to be part of the original design but much of the content was created by the modding team.

The restored content and the restored planet are modders best attempts to give us the original "complete" game as visualized by Obsidian developers.

* Do a clean install (above).
* Install version 1.8.3 of the Restored Content mod.
* Install planet M4-78 mod version 1.1.
* Install your no-cd patch or cracked .exe file (if you have one). GOG version doesn't have a cd-check.
Fire up the game and enjoy all the restored content.

NOTE: If you have "other" mods you want to use, make sure they're compatible with the Restored Content and Restored Planet mods, and install them _after_ these two packs.

The Mods I like:
* Restored Content
* Restored Planet M4-78
* Powered Armor for Bao Dur
* Skip Peragus
* Easy Swoop Racing for TSL

=== Config Hacks ===

swkotor2.ini set the fullscreen under [Graphic options] to 0.

Sound fix: I initially had a problem with sound not working, but I found that if I replaced the Miles sound system DLL (Mss32.dll) in the game's install directory with an older one from KotOR 1, it began to work fine. The version of the DLL that came with KotOR 2 is 6.6.7.0 while KotOR 1 has the 3.0.0.0 version.

=== Widescreen For KOTOR 2 ===

The difference between the 1920x1200 and 1920x1080(1080P) is the aspect ratio (16:10 vs 16:9) and 120 pixels vertically.

Cowspot: 1920x1200. Needs the 16:10 HUD ratio.

=== Class Breakdown ===

If you want a prestige, you need to make sure to save Visas and then talk to Kreia at level 15. You also need to be at least 75% Light or Dark Side.

Base Classes

* Jedi Guardian - Lots of Vitality and little force, this means you are able to run around and punch everybody in the face with a little help from the force.

* Jedi Sentinel - All around character with a large skill set, about equal in vitality and force points so you can either punch people in the face or sit back and use the force.

* Jedi Consular - Not much vitality but you get a lot of force points, this allows you to sit back and use your force for most of the game, but be warned, this class is not recommended for first time players as it is difficult to defeat multiple enemies with this class at times.

Consulars have such a mastery of the force that being a Consular + Master is unnecessary, and that going Consular/Watchman or Consular/WM is better to suppliment the Consular's lack of physical prowess.

=== KOTOR 2: Earning Influence ===

* Kreia: She prefers you take a neutral attitude and look after yourself first. Choosing dialogyue options that indicate you're using people or unconcerned about their greater good will earn influence with her. She'll be delighted if you tell her you're using her! Also, she likes to push you around - apologizing and/or letting her push you around tends to gain influence.

* Atton: Atton is pretty easy. Just take him out, take his side, praise his skills. If you do Dark acts, reassure him that he or the group still have value to you. With enough Influence, he'll become a Jedi. Level 12 is a good breakpoint to stop taking Scoundrel levels. Wait@12 for Jedi levels.

* Mira is another fairly easy one. Just chat with her and don't take her on the HK murder spree (she won't approve). She can be persuaded to make deadly grenades, and is best if you either hold all levels as a Jedi, or switched after 20.

* Bao Dur: He's another easy one. Just take him out and do good deeds with him around. He has some dialogues on Dantooine. On Nar Shadda he responds positively to healing the sick homeless Refugee. Because he's squishy I like to take him to level 10 on Telos, and then let him hold levels to take Jedi. With the mod pack power armor he could possibly stay at 8. If you feel influencing him is a waste of time, put all level-ups into Intelligence and make him your crafting specialist.

* HK-47: HK is a slippery one. You have to take him on a Dark-gaining murder spree. He has a few handy targets that don't break useful quests.
# A random guy standing outside his apartment on Telos. Loot a box in his home to initiate combat. 
# The receptionist in the Exchange office on Telos. Remember not to scare her off!
# The alien crew waiting for their captain in the storage containers on Nar Shadda. (No dark side points for this one!)
# The herd alien whose blueprints were stolen in the containers on Nar Shadda. He'll drop a prototype when he dies.

* Visas: She's easy. Just chat her up and take her out on a couple quest runs. When you first meet her you have a one-time chance to get her special sight power. Save before the talk so you don't fail the influence roll. Make sure to get her a decent rating in Security as she'll need it late in the game.
